{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 PURGATORIO CANTO 21}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 1.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   From at least the time of Tommaseo (comm. to vv. 1-3), commentators dealing with \softline
this opening verse have cited the opening (and other passages) of Dante's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (I.i.1): 'As the \softline
Philosopher [Aristotle] says in the beginning of the First Philosophy [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Metaphysics}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.i], all of \softline
humankind naturally desires to know.'  Bosco/Reggio (comm. to vv. 1-6), however, make an \softline
important distinction.  Since here the protagonist is presented with a miracle, the moment in \softline
which a soul is finally prepared to rise to God, the following reference (vv. 2-3) to the waters of \softline
eternal life in the episode in John's gospel 'confirms the notion that the natural desire for \softline
knowledge cannot be satisfied except by Revelation, thus going beyond the affirmations found in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (I.i.1; I.i.9; III.xv.4) normally cited by the commentators, which are limited to \softline
philosophical knowledge.'  It is interesting to note that Pietro di Dante (Pietro1, comm. to vv. 1-3) cites the beginning of Aristotle's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Metaphysics}{\plain \fs24 \f1  to make a highly similar point, separating \softline
Aristotelian }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 scientia mundana}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (knowledge of this world) from experience of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 divina gratia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (divine \softline
grace).  On the distance between the formulations found in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  and those presented here, \softline
see also Hollander (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Allegory in Dante's "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: Princeton University Press, \softline
1969]), pp. 68-69.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 2-3.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The obvious reference to the passage in John's gospel (4:5-15) has not escaped many \softline
readers.  The Samaritan woman who finds Jesus, unprepared for the task of drawing water, at her \softline
well, ends up being eager to taste the 'water' that he offers as replacement for that which seems so \softline
necessary at noon of a warm day in the desert, for it 'fiet in eo fons aquae }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 salientis}{\plain \fs24 \f1  in vitam \softline
aeternam' ([italics added] shall become in him a fountain of water springing up into life \softline
everlasting).  In the Vulgate the present participle }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 salientis}{\plain \fs24 \f1  may refer to the water or indeed to the \softline
drinker, rising up into eternal life.  It is worth keeping this potential grammatical ambiguity in \softline
mind, for that second reading applies precisely to the condition of Statius, who has just now come \softline
to that moment in his posthumous existence: he is ready to take on the life of a soul in paradise; \softline
he himself is ready to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 salire}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (rise up).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Strangely enough, there is dispute among the commentators as to the metaphoric nature of \softline
the water offered by Jesus.  For the first quarter millennium all who dealt with this question \softline
offered the obvious interpretation: divine grace.  Then in the nineteenth century, beginning with \softline
Portirelli (comm. to vv. 1-6), some interpreters were of the opinion that the water referred either \softline
to human knowledge of God or to that knowledge possessed alone by God.  Another group, the \softline
first of them Tommaseo (comm. to vv. 1-3), thought that it signified 'truth,' although exactly \softline
which kind varied, from Porena's (comm. to vv. 1-6) sense that for Dante it meant truth in general \softline
to Giacalone's (comm. to vv. 1-6) view that it means the truth found in Revelation alone.  Surely \softline
the early commentators were correct.  The water that the Samaritan woman asks for is that of \softline
eternal life, which comes alone from the grace of God.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab As some commentators have pointed out, John's word for the Samaritan is }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 mulier}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
(woman), while Dante has used a diminutive (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 femminetta}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ).  Giacalone (comm. to vv. 1-6) thinks \softline
of the form more as a 'commiserative' than as a 'diminutive,' i.e., we are to think of this woman's \softline
absolute ordinariness as an encouragement to our own need for exactly such satisfaction of our \softline
'thirst.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 4-6.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante has rarely portrayed his protagonist as being beset by so many distractions.  
He desperately wants to understand the meaning both of the earthquake and of the song \softline
accompanying it; he and Virgil are trying to move ahead as quickly as possible, picking their way \softline
among the clutter of the penitents; he continues to feel a sense of grief at their punishment, \softline
despite its obvious rightness.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 7-9.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Announced with its solemn biblical stylistic flourish (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Ed ecco}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [And lo]), the \softline
reminiscence of Luke 24:13-16 (a passage that begins 'Et ecce') reminds the reader of two of \softline
Christ's disciples (Dante's first commentators at times incorrectly identify them as James and John; \softline
it is clear that one of the two is named Cleopas [24:18], while the other is perhaps his wife \softline
[24:29], in which case she may well have been known as Mary [John 19:25]), walking on the road \softline
to Emmaus when Christ joined them and walked with them, unrecognized.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 10-14.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Statius's unmistakable resemblance to Christ risen, his figural relation to Jesus, \softline
makes him, technically, not a 'figure' of Christ but a 'fulfillment' of Him, which is theologically \softline
awkward.  Hollander (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Allegory in Dante's "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: Princeton University Press, \softline
1969]), pp. 67-70, argues for the technical reference of the word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 ombra}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (shade) here, grounded in \softline
the language of the Christian interpretation of Scripture, discovered, indeed, in this very chapter \softline
of Luke's gospel (24:27), when Jesus teaches his disciples the figural method of understanding the \softline
Old Testament.  (See Heilbronn ["The Prophetic Role of Statius in Dante's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatory}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante \softline
Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  95 [1977], p. 58, for a similar view.)\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab How, some commentators have asked, perhaps beginning with Manfredi Porena (comm. \softline
to vv. 7-13), could Dante and Virgil }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 see}{\plain \fs24 \f1  that Statius was behind them?  They could not.  Now, \softline
narrating the scene, the poet, knowing that Statius came up from behind, says that he did so.  \softline
They first became aware of him when he spoke -- at which point, as the text says, they turned \softline
around.  As the risen Christ walked along beside Cleopas and his wife, who did not recognize \softline
him, so does the 'resurrected' Statius walk up behind Dante and Virgil, who do not at first know \softline
that he is there.  In both scenes it is also true that 'the two who were on the way' do not know \softline
with whom they converse until much later (see Luke 24:35, when they break bread with their \softline
'new' acquaintance in their home; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXI.91, when this soul's identity is finally made plain).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Another problem here is caused by the grammatical ambiguity of the phrase 'guardando la \softline
turba che giace': who is doing the looking, Statius or Dante and Virgil?  Grammatically both are \softline
possible.  Both proximity and common sense move a reader to the latter possibility: Dante and \softline
Virgil, the 'noi' that is closer to the gerund than Statius's 'ombra,' are looking down at the shades, \softline
as we know (from }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XX.143, where they are also 'guardando'; XXI.6).  Statius, having just \softline
come from lying prostrate, is more likely to be looking ahead and above, where he is finally \softline
allowed to direct himself.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For the present tense of the verb }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 giace}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , problematic in whatever solution one proposes for \softline
the last question, see the note to vv. 22-24.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Statius's first words join him to the tradition of fraternal purgatorial greeting on the part of \softline
the penitents we have so far heard addressing Dante: Belacqua (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IV.127); Oderisi (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
XI.82); Sapia (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XIII.94); Marco (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XVI.65); Adrian (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XIX.133).  See notes to \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IV.127 and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XIX.133.  For a complete listing of all uses of 'frate' as form of address in \softline
the last two }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantiche}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IV.127.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Singleton's dependence on Sinclair's translation of this passage is betrayed by his comment \softline
(comm. to vv. 10-13), which has Statius looking at the crowd of penitents at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 his}{\plain \fs24 \f1  feet, while the 
translation has Dante and Virgil doing the looking.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For the source of Statius's greeting, see the words of Christ to his apostles, the second \softline
scene of his resurrected life on earth in Luke's gospel (Luke 24:36): 'Pax vobis: ego sum, nolite \softline
timere' (Peace unto you: I am, have no fear).  In the next verse of Luke the apostles indeed do \softline
show fear; and we may remember how fearful Dante was when the earth shook beneath him at the \softline
end of the last canto (vv. 128-129; 135).  William Stephany ("Biblical Allusions to Conversion in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXI," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Stanford Italian Review}{\plain \fs24 \f1  3 [1983]), pp. 161-62, sees a connection with biblical \softline
moments (in the narratives involving Cleopas and the Samaritan woman) in which 'characters are \softline
frightened either by Jesus' birth or rebirth.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 14-15.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The nature of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cenno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (sign) made in response by Virgil has long puzzled the \softline
commentators.  We can say one thing with something like certainty: Virgil's gesture is not a \softline
spoken one, since he makes some sort of gesture and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 then}{\plain \fs24 \f1  begins to speak (verse 16).  Many early \softline
and some later commentators have liked the idea that in response Virgil said 'et cum spiritu tuo' \softline
(and with your spirit as well), a liturgical reply.  Yet it surely seems impossible that Dante would \softline
have first presented Virgil as speaking and then immediately afterwards as }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 beginning to speak}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  \softline
And so it is clearly preferable to understand that Virgil made some sort of physical gesture.  \softline
Perhaps the most sensible gloss remains that of Benvenuto (comm. to vv. 14-18): 'with similar \softline
reverence [Virgil] lowered his head to him.'  Previously Dante has clearly distinguished among \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 parole}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 mani}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cenni}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (words, [actions of] hands, and signs) at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.50; and he will \softline
distinguish between }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 dir}{\plain \fs24 \f1  and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cenno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (speech and sign) at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXVII.139.  In fact, in the \softline
fifteen uses of the word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cenno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  in the poem, this would be the only one in which it referred to \softline
speech, as Steiner (comm. to verse 15) points out, adding that Virgil, as a pagan inhabitant of \softline
Limbo, is never permitted either to pronounce sacred phrases or to perform actions pertaining to \softline
Christian ritual (e.g., genuflexion).  The word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cenno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  appears frequently in the poem (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  III.117, \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IV.98, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VIII.5, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XVI.116, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXI.138, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXII.8, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.50, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VI.141, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
XII.129, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XIX.86, here, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXII.27, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXVII.139; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XV.71, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXII.101).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For the ingenious but perhaps not eventually acceptable notion that Virgil's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cenno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  'may \softline
very well be an embrace, a gesture analogous to the liturgical Kiss of Peace' see Heilbronn ("The \softline
Prophetic Role of Statius in Dante's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatory}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  95 [1977]), pp. 58-65.  Had Virgil \softline
been a Christian, Dante might very well have chosen to make Heilbronn right.  However, see \softline
James Albrecht ("'Il cenno ch'a ci{\f3 \'62} si conface' [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  21.15]," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Electronic Bulletin of the \softline
Dante Society of America}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [February 2002]), who argues that Virgil's gesture is the sign of the \softline
cross, offered without the accompanying response to the hopeful wish 'Dominus det nobis suam \softline
pacem' (May God grant us His peace) found in breviaries and in the liturgy of the hours: 'Et vitam \softline
eternam' (And eternal life); in Albrecht's view it is what Virgil }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 did not say}{\plain \fs24 \f1  that is focal to the \softline
scene.  (For clear examples of facial gestures as }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cenni}{\plain \fs24 \f1  in this very canto, see verse 104, Virgil's \softline
look that calls for silence and verse 109, Dante's smile that is a hint.)\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 16-18.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's wish for Statius is touching, in part because it has been accomplished, \softline
since Statius is already substantially one of the blessed, only awaiting a change in his accidental \softline
state, which will be accomplished in less than a day.  While the poem does not show him there, its \softline
givens make it plain that, had Dante chosen to do so, Statius could have been observed seated in \softline
the rose in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXXII; he is there by the time Dante ascends into the heavens at the \softline
beginning of the next }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , or so we may assume.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \ul0 \tab Virgil's insistence on his own eternal home is a moving reminder of his tragic situation in \softline
this comic poem.  Statius's salvation comes closer than anyone else's in showing how near Virgil \softline
himself came to eternal blessedness, as the next canto will make clear.  And, once we learn (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
XXII.67-73) that it was Virgil who was responsible, by means of his fourth }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Eclogue}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , for the \softline
conversion of Statius, we consider these lines with a still more troubled heart.  For remarks in a \softline
similar vein see Stephany ("Biblical Allusions to Conversion in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXI," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Stanford Italian \softline
Review}{\plain \fs24 \f1  3 [1983]), p. 158n.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 19-21.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   For Statius's miscomprehension of Dante's condition, see the note to the next \softline
tercet.  The physical reason for it is that, because the travelers are out of the sun's rays on the far \softline
side of the mountain, Dante's body casts no revealing shadow, and Statius takes Virgil's \softline
confession of his own plight to apply to both of these 'shades.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 19.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   For }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 parte}{\plain \fs24 \f1  used here and in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIX.16 as an adverb, a Florentine provincialism, \softline
meaning 'meanwhile,' see Moore (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Contributions to the Textual Criticism of the "Divina \softline
Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1889]), pp. 398-99, citing Benvenuto as \softline
previously making the same point in both instances.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 22-24.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's remarks suggest to Statius that the (remaining three) P's on Dante's \softline
forehead indicate a special status, namely that he is bound for Glory -- just as is Statius.  But did \softline
Statius have these marks incised on }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 his}{\plain \fs24 \f1  forehead?  Had he, they would now all be erased but for \softline
this last, which would probably disappear, along with Dante's, before the beginning of the next \softline
canto (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXII.3, where we learn the angel has wiped Dante's fifth P from his brow).  He \softline
would have spent, we will be able to compute from information gleaned from verse 68 and from \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXII.92-93, as many as 300 years in ante-purgatory and/or on some or all of the first \softline
three terraces, since it is 1204 years since his death in the year 96 and he has had to remain over \softline
400 years on the fourth terrace and over 500 on this one.  Thus, had he borne signs on his \softline
forehead, these would originally have been as many as five and as few as two.  However, there is \softline
no reason to believe that he, or any other penitent not here in the flesh, has had his brow incised \softline
with P's.  (See the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IX.112.)  For other reasons to believe that only Dante is incised, \softline
see Hollander ("The Letters on Dante's Brow [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . 9.112 and 21.22-24]," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Electronic Bulletin of \softline
the Dante Society of America}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [January 2002]); for an opposing view see Nicola Fosca \softline
("Beatitudini e processo di purgazione," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Electronic Bulletin of the Dante Society of America}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
[February 2002]).  And for an attempt to deal with the problem raised by the present tense of the \softline
verb }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 profila}{\plain \fs24 \f1  as indicating that the warder habitually inscribes the P's on sinners, see, again, \softline
Hollander's note in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 EBDSA}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , where he argues, following a suggestion offered by Chimenz \softline
(comm. to vv. 22-24), that this present has the significance of a past and that we should \softline
understand that only Dante is to be understood as having had his forehead incised.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 25-30.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The circumlocution describes Lachesis, the second of the three Fates of classical \softline
mythology.  'At the birth of every mortal, Clotho, the spinning fate, was supposed to wind upon \softline
the distaff of Lachesis, the alotting fate, a certain amount of yarn; the duration of the life of the \softline
individual being the length of time occupied in spinning the thread, which, when complete, was \softline
severed by Atropos, the inevitable fate' (Toynbee, "Laches{\f3 \'58}s" [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Concise Dante Dictionary}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ]).  For \softline
Atropos, see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXXIII.126.  This is Virgil's long-winded way of saying that Dante was still 
in the body when he was summoned to guide him through the afterworld.  For Dante's likely \softline
dependence upon Statius for the names of the three Fates, see Ettore Paratore, "Stazio" \softline
(ED.1976.5), pp. 422b-423a.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 33.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   What exactly Virgil means by his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 scola}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (teaching of Dante) has been a matter of some \softline
debate, featuring predictable allegorizations, e.g., Virgil as reason, Statius as moral philosophy, \softline
Beatrice as theology.  None of these has the merit of being immediately (or eventually?) \softline
convincing.  The last time we have heard the word was at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IV.94, where the poet referred \softline
to the group of poets (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 la bella scola}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) headed by Homer, and perhaps, 'reading Dante by Dante,' \softline
we should keep this simplest explanation in clear view.  Virgil, informed by all that a pagan poet \softline
can know, will guide Dante as best he can.  Once we reach the question of the nature of the \softline
human soul, in Canto XXV, he will give way to Statius, who, as a Christian, understands things \softline
about the nature of the human soul's relationship to divinity of which Virgil is simply ignorant.  \softline
There is no reason to believe, one might add, that Beatrice could not have instructed Dante about \softline
this question, or that Statius could not have told him anything that Beatrice will reveal in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  All saved Christians, in this poem, are capable of knowing all things in God.  The \softline
rewards of Heaven are not only affective, but intellectual.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab We should also be aware of Beatrice's use of the same word, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 scola}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
XXXIII.85 to denigrate Dante's own nearly disastrous adventures in what she seems to consider \softline
his overbold philosophizing.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 34-39.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   At last Virgil asks Statius the two questions that have so vexed Dante; for a third \softline
time the importance of the salvation of Statius is underlined.  See notes to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XX.145-151 and to vv. 4-6 of this canto.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 40-60.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Statius first establishes the meteorology of the mountain.  There is no 'weather' \softline
encountered above the upper limit of ante-purgatory, but below that limit there is.  Up here the \softline
